[[File:Ulysses, 1922.djvu|thumb|600px|center|page=408]]
<br>
==Annotations==
'''''Nos omnes biberimus viridum toxicum diabolus capiat posterioria nostria'''''{{spaces|5}}(''Dog Latin'') ''We will all drink green poison [and] the devil take the hindmost''.<ref>Gifford (1988) 446.<br>Thornton (1968) 354.</ref> The ''green poison'' is [[w:Absinthe|absinthe]], which Stephen referred to earlier in the day as ''green fairy'' ([[Annotations_to_James_Joyce's_Ulysses/Proteus/043|043.02]]), a name by which it is known in France. ''[[wikt:devil take the hindmost|The devil take the hindmost]]'' is a common expression. ''Posterioria nostria'' is not real Latin, though the meaning (''our posteriors'') is clear. Presumably this comment is added by Mulligan after Stephen has ordered absinthe for everyone; Mulligan's Latin, unlike Stephen's, is not always correct ([[Annotations_to_James_Joyce's_Ulysses/Oxen_of_the_Sun/384|384.15-18]]) and he has been preoccupied with posteriors before ([[Annotations_to_James_Joyce's_Ulysses/Scylla_and_Charybdis/192|192.36 ff.]] and [[Annotations_to_James_Joyce's_Ulysses/Scylla_and_Charybdis/197|197.13]]).


