<br>
==Annotations==
'''''haud ignarus malorum miseris succurrere disco'''''{{spaces|5}}(''Latin'') ''Not at all unacquainted with misfortunes, I learn to succour the wretched''.<ref>Gifford (1988) 537.<br>Thornton (1968) 431.</ref> The narrator (Bloom?) has adapted a line (1:630) from [[w:Virgil|Virgil's]] epic poem the ''[[w:Aeneid|Aeneid]]'':<ref>[http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0054%3Abook%3D1%3Acard%3D613 Virgil, ''Aeneid'' 1:613-642.]</ref> ''Non ignara mali, miseris succurrere disco'' (''Not unacquainted with misfortune, I learn to succour the wretched''). [[w:Dido (Queen of Carthage)|Dido]] says this to Aeneas.

